More than 7,000 cassava farmers in Kilifi county are set to benefit from an EU-funded initiative to increase their acreage.The initiative dubbed &lsquo;Strengthening the competitiveness of the cassava value chain in Kenya&rsquo; is aimed at increasing food and nutrition security and improving incomes.The EU has given out a Sh700 million grant towards the programme which is currently being implemented by Self Help Africa, Ustadi Foundation among a host of other partners.Speaking after the launch of the initiative at Mnarani Hotel in Kilifi town on Saturday, Self Help Africa country director Rebbeca Mkuye said 7,000 farmers will be trained on how to grow cassava.She expressed optimism that after the end of the five-year implementation period, farmers will be able to increase cassava yields.